John,<br><br>
 Got a large charge out of your tips.... though I might have a little to add to them but here was the funny part. When I joined the 101st I expected, well maybe all of the troops to be jump qualified... Humm... turned out that less than 10% had ever made a jump... Not that it mattered a whole hell of a lot, never did jump in 'Nam .. well save for the times when the slick driver would have a little fun with his load of grunts and hover about 2 feet about some nice TALL grass... First step will get ya.. Did make a couple of jumps  out of Danang... kept the Jump Pay coming. One of the E6's got a couple of us to try jumping his way... let's see get in a c130 doing 'bout 90-110 at oh 'bout 100 or so feet off the deck, stand on the back ramp which is about half way down, look forward ... backup till only toes on the ramp and  the second he tells you pull the rip... 8 seconds later your down. Shiiiiiiiiiiiiiitttttttttt. What a rush. As he told us later... see if you've heard this one before .. 'WHAT you wanna LIVE FOREVER ? Well your in the worng place for that !&quot;<br><br>
 Hey... Guys no matter if you were in a slick, an F4, drove a duce/half whatever that SUPPORTED grunts like me in the bush... We Were All On The Same Team. I have read that the support personal to grunt ratio was 7 to 1 but that is unfair, hey where can you go camping today and have that sorta service... and FLOWN RIGHT TO THE CAMP SITE ! <br><br>
I still remember during the first few days at Fort Jackson the Army gave us Draft'ts the standard test the was to determin what you were best suited for in the Army.... Yea right it's 196x and you wanna know what I'm best suited for ? That's rich... But as I read the questions one ask if you liked to go camping ! I bust out laughing at that one... The  DI who was hearding us around took a dim view of my humor to say the least and I was introduced to the Horz excercise that I came to know quite well...... But I was young , stupid and foolish then... Somewhere between then and my leaving the service I changed a lot... Now I was a little older, just a stupid, a LOT more foolish but add a very proud member of a team that had truly done something important, with a whole lot of really GREAT Men &amp; Women<br><br>
 POINT: We all had it hard, that's what made us what we are,<br>
        Proud Veterans. Period the end. I would not trade my         time in 'Nam for anything. It made us what we are         now and forever.<br><br>
WELL there MAYBE one exception to that.. We had a cook in the 1/327th that I sware was out to kill us all.. we kept making 'HIS' mess-hall dirty... What you want us to take a damn shower before breakfast ? You see it raining out there ? Track in WHAT mud ? Oh well.... Back to the c-rats....
<p><code>--   (Gary 'J.') </code><p>


